My topic: Should the legal voting age be raised to 21?

Thesis Statement: The legal voting age should be raised to 21 because 18-year-olds generally are not fully informed of political issues, are more easily persuaded by the viewpoints of relatives and peers, and have not had a chance to become informed on political issues.

Proposition Statement: The legal voting age should be raised to 21 because it will produce more informed voters, give youth a chance to become informed on political events, and offer a more stable foundation for our political landscape.

1. On page 115, last full paragraph, Parenti is describing a story that involves a VCSU operation taking place at a gas station in Fresno, California, "As the first cruiser approaches, six young African American men on the corner start moving away: that's suspicious behavior, probable cause for a stop." Just from this short excerpt of the story, I can already identify an issue with present day policing techniques, racial profiling. Although the area in this story has a past of being a hot spot for criminal behavior, it still shows how police are assuming the worst in African American men and women.

On pages 116-117, last full paragraph and first full paragraph respectively, Parenti is describing another story involving a VCSU operation in which, "A unit has 'contact' on the far end of the Dog Pound, and on foot an individual has fled the scene of a traffic stop, entering a nearby house... Technically [the officers] are not in hot pursuit and have no right to storm the building, but they look angry and their guns make it seem serious, so the elderly woman behind the black metal security gate quickly consents to a search." From the last part of this excerpt, where 'the elderly woman behind the black metal security gate quickly consents to a search,' it can be concluded that if the officers had not been carrying an immense amount of firepower and high tech gadgets, the elderly woman most likely would not have consented to a search without a warrant. This presents the argument of which I would like to write on, the unjust behavior police present that goes against the fourth amendment. 

2. The topic of racial profiling is a severe social injustice in that it is the equivalent of modern day segregation. Although we no longer segregate restaurants and schools by race, the way we treat minorities, primarily African Americans and Latinos, shows just how far we have to go in order to be a just society. One example from the text that perfectly illustrates my point is shown on page 168, sixth sentence, when Parenti states, "Prison also mops up huge numbers of poor African American, Latino, and Native American people." This statement shows how cops assume that almost all criminals are of the races identified by Parenti in this last statement. If you have seen the television series Breaking Bad, then you should know that Caucasian people can be criminals as well. 

In regards to my second identified topic, that of the the unjust police behavior present that goes against the fourth amendment, there are multiple points I would like to discuss the contemporary relevance of this topic. In recent news articles, I have seen numerous stories of police officers getting in trouble for conducting a traffic stop without real probable cause or reasonable suspicion. I personally feel these two phrases are extremely generalized and they give police too much power. When police stop a car for no good reason, the actual reason seems to be that of racial profiling or an unjust search. This topic is a very big social injustice because it causes everyday people to become afraid every time they come in contact with a police officer, or even see a police vehicle while driving at the speed limit.

1. Based on my interest in the topic, I have decided to focus my research on racial profiling. This topic has been under intense debate in the US for the last few decades and I am interested into why it has become such an issue in modern day politics. 

 

In order to narrow my research, I will be focusing on the use of racial profiling in routine traffic stops. The act of using race as an indicator of "reasonable suspicion" is giving too much power to law enforcement officials.

1. Based on my interest in the topic, I have decided to focus my research on racial profiling. This topic has been under intense debate in the US for the last few decades and I am interested into why it has become such an issue in modern day politics. 

In order to narrow my research, I will be focusing on the use of racial profiling in routine traffic stops. The act of using race as an indicator of "reasonable suspicion" is giving too much power to law enforcement officials.

2. The sources I plan on using as part of my research include:

        1) Baumgartner, Frank R., et al. Suspect Citizens : What 20 Million Traffic Stops Tell Us about Policing and Race. Cambridge University Press, 2018. EBSCOhost, search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=cat07712a&AN=flc.437007&site=eds-live.

                a) This book analyzes data pulled from police departments across the nation that shows the relationship between routine traffic stops and racial profiling. By looking at why the police officers pulled a motorist over, the rate of arrests as a result of the traffic stops, and any abuse or mistreatment of civilians by officers, this book illustrates the showcases the real issue behind racial profiling in the United States.

                b) This source will help me develop background knowledge on my topic by presenting me with data and statistics that will help support my argument and provide me insight into the reasons why police officers use racial profiling as a means of arrest or abuse. 

        2) Epp, Charles R., et al. Pulled over : How Police Stops Define Race and Citizenship. The University of Chicago Press, 2014. EBSCOhost, search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=cat07712a&AN=flc.172985&site=eds-live.

                a) This book identifies the reasoning behind racial profiling by police officers and the justification for those reasons given by those officers by interviewing both the officers and civilians involved in the traffic stops to provide clear insight into both why the officers use racial profiling as a means to pull over a motorist and how the motorist reacts when they are pulled over for that reason alone.

               b) This source will help me develop background knowledge on my topic by providing me with very detailed insight into the minds and thought patterns of the parties involved in traffic stops in which racial profiling was evident. By looking at both sides of the issue, this source will give me more opportunities to enhance my argument and help me avoid becoming biased on this particular topic.

3. The Southern region of the United States, primarily the South Eastern region, has been the epicenter of race-fueled hate crimes and racial profiling ever since the Revolutionary War. The relationship between African American civilians and law enforcement officials has been a rising issue in recent years. Although some progress has been made in regards to the treatment of African American citizens, the rate at which law enforcement officials are wrongly pulling over motorists is dramatically slowing the pace of achieving social justice in the United States (Baumgartner et. al 29). One can easily assume that this is simply an opinion being presented as facts, however, data never lies. A dataset pulled from a database that holds the records of every traffic stop in the state of North Carolina from 2002 through 2016 shows "that about 20 percent of [adolescent] pedestrian encounters... 'almost [never] turn up guns (0.11 percent of all stops) or other contraband (1.5 percent).'" (Baumgartner et al 29). After looking at these statistics, it's difficult to argue against the fact that law enforcement officials are using biased political views to identify potential criminals. North Carolina may be the only state represented in this report, though these types of trends can be found across the United States.

1. Traffic stops on the grounds of reasonable suspicion for drug possession should be banned because they are ineffective at preventing and stopping crime, create distrust between law enforcement officials and the community, and are the primary cause of racial biases among police departments.

 

Another source I analyzed during the research process was an academic journal article written by Jocelyn Simonson. Throughout the article, Simonson illustrates the history and meaning of the current national police reform. While introducing the contents of the article, the author states, “that policing practices should reduce crime, make people feel safe, and promote trust between police officers and communities.” (Simonson 793) While there are minor changes being brought about on a national level, state and local law enforcement agencies are working together through an approach that Simonson describes as an “instrumental approach” (Simonson 794). The overall goal of this approach is for state and local law enforcement agencies to work together by collecting data from body cam footage, crash reports, and surveillance footage to accurately identify and prevent police brutality and act against the officers involved (Simonson 797). By collecting and analyzing these datasets, analysts can identify trends, predict situational outcomes, and present statistics to help inform, persuade, and inspire government officials to make changes in the way law enforcement takes place (Simonson 808). As an Information Systems Major, I fully support this approach because of the way it presents facts and supports decision making rather than using the intuition of biased sources to make changes in the criminal justice system. Although data analysis and visualization tools are not perfect, they can identify accurate data trends and predictions in a timely manner. One program that is currently being used for this purpose is known as, “CompStat for Justice”, “which provides the ability to add additional metrics such as use of force statistics and the results of community surveys.” (Simonson 808) This example illustrates the current capabilities of the law enforcement agencies and the potential positive impact it can have on police reform movements across the United States.

** I know this is from my Exploratory Research Essay, but I plan on incorporating much of the same types of sources and materials for this essay. **

QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS

1. The Social Network, a film released in 2010, combines fact and fiction about an idea of Harvard Student Mark Zuckerberg that he and some classmates turned into a succes fou.

2. The screenplay was adapted from The Accidental Billionaires, a 2009 book by Ben Mezrich.

3. While The Social Network lost out to The King's Speech for the Academy Award for best picture, the former won Oscars for best adapted screenplay, original score, and film editing. 

4. Many critics, including Peter Travers in Rolling Stone magazine, praised the Facebook film, while Zuckerberg pointed out its inaccuracies. 

5. The term social networking had a meaning of its own before it became synonymous with social-networking websites.

6. The word facebook was originally the nickname of a publication of photographs that some colleges gave to students at the beginning of the school year to help them get to know each other.

7. Two earlier versions of the Facebook site were called Facemash and Thefacebook.

8. Harvard has not allowed filming on its campus since Love Story, a 1970 release, so The Social Network was filmed elsewhere.

9. The movie about building Facebook is hardly the first time Hollywood has woven fiction into real-life events. The 1912 sinking of the ocean liner Titanic is another story that was changed in a film.

10. Not everyone loves Facebook; some people consider it the antisocial network.

Section P-2: Semicolons

  1. Steroids are performance-enhancing drugs, indeed; they build muscle mass and strength, which lead to better results in competition.
  2. Steroids are synthetic forms of the male hormone testosterone; megadoses of steroids give users an unfair advantage.
  3. Males in good health usually produce less than ten milligrams of testosterone a day; athletes on steroids swallow or inject hundreds of milligrams a day.
  4. In adults, steroids cause rapid weight gain, problems with blood clotting, and heart attacks; in adolescents they can shut down bone growth.
  5. Signs of steroid use are jaundice, or yellow skin, sudden combative behavior, excessive vomiting that lasts more than a few days, and swollen feet.
  6. Athletes who later admitted steroid use include Mark McGwire and Barry Bonds, the baseball stars; Marion Jones, the track star; and Lance Armstrong, the cyclist.
  7. McGwire surpassed Roger Maris’s season home-run record of sixty; Bonds beat McGwire’s number and set the record for most career home runs as well.
  8. In 2013, Alex Rodriguez was suspended for 211 games for allegedly using steroids; thirteen other major-league baseball players were also suspended, but A-Rod was the only one to appeal his suspension.
  9. A 2012 report by the Associated Press claimed college football players use steroids; it suggested that colleges knowingly look the other way.
  10. Books about steroid use in athletics include Game of Shadows, 2007; Bases Loaded, 2009; and Steroids: A New Look,

For this assignment, I chose to study Arches National Park. The landform I will analyze is Delicate Arch. 

1. Some of the special conditions and factors that influence the development of landforms in deserts include erosion, the presence of joints within the rocks, and desert storms.

2. The role of running water, erosion and deposition in Arches is that erosion is what helps create the beautiful arches seen across the landscape of the national park, and the running water may change to create a natural bridge which is another type of landform found in this park. As for how these factor influence Delicate Arch, this arch was created by erosion and by joints being created in the lower potions of the rock which made the lower potion weaker and eventually collapse, leaving the arch we see today.

3. The role of wind in shaping both the park and Delicate Arch is that it helps shape the rocks and natural formations found in the park by blowing debris such as sand and smaller rocks which slowly chips away at the landforms. This sometimes causes the landforms to collapse if they are too weak.

4. There is some evidence of alluvial fans by the natural wasting of ancient streams, though I do not see any evidence of playas. I know there are alluvial fans because there used to be strong streams flowing through the park.

5. There are buttes and mesas by the natural rock formations caused by wind patterns and erosion. I know this because of the wind patterns seen across the park and the mesas seen in photographs.

1. Based off the first image, the presence of jointing is shown in the straight lines along the rock and at the base that form the joint between the rock and the ground. Chemical weathering can be seen by the changing of colors within the rock. This is evidence that different forms of chemical weathering took place. Physical weathering can be seen by the difference of texture on the surface of the rock. Overall, weathering is very evident in this photograph.

2. Based off the second image, the lines shown in the rock provide evidence for both vertical and horizontal joints in this region. Also present is another variety of colors in the rock that provides evidence of chemical weathering. Also evident is the presence of physical weathering which is shown in the unique rock formation throughout this valley. Physical weathering can also be seen in the various holes in the rocks.

3. Based on my understanding on the formation of arches, the lower portions of a sliver of sedimentary rock can become weakened and collapse which exposes the stronger and more resilient rock above, forming an arch.

1. For my first observation, I chose to analyze the time lapse of Lassen National Forest and Volcanic Park in California. One of the first major changes I noticed in this time laps was the massive deforestation that took place in 1992 and 1993. It seems as in that calendar year, a third of the trees were cut down for human use, or for the purposes of urbanization. The next major change I noticed took place in 2003 where structures, most likely homes, began to be built in increasing numbers until 2012 when there are now hundreds of structures. One consequence I could see these major changes having on the landscape in the change in the natural wildlife's ecosystem. When that large of a portion of trees is removed from a forest, animals such as birds need to re-shelter to survive.

2. For my second observation, I chose to analyze the time lapse of the Oakland Bay Bridge in San Francisco, California. Although there wasn't any massive changes at one time during the time lapse, one major change I saw that gradually took place was the number of industrial structures being built on the west side of the Bay. I believe they are either warehouses or shipping yards because of the size and shape of the buildings and where they are located. One positive consequence I think could occur as a result of this change is major economic growth because of the new transportation route being created for the shipping yards with the bridge linking the two sides of the Bay together.

3. For my third observation, I chose to analyze the time lapse of Fort McMurray in Alberta, Canada. In the beginning of the time lapse, no noticeable changes took place. However, once the turn of the century took place, it seemed as if Fort McMurray went from a tiny farming community to a major industrial powerhouse for mining and farming. Large tracts of land were transformed from green fields to agricultural or industrial warehouses built for providing materials in bulk to the masses. One consequence I can see occurring in the future is the change in the region's climate. Since there is now a lack of greenery in the area, the potential for wildfires or storms could increase because of the dramatic changes.

4. For my final observation, I chose to analyze the time lapse of Dubai, United Arab Emirates. The landscape started out as a basic coastal desert with no sight of any metropolitan areas. However, over time, shipping lanes and a large number of building began to show up and made Dubai into a a global industrial powerhouse. One consequence I can see happening due to this dramatic change is the growth of opportunity for labor and markets because of the new found oil fields, I am assuming since that is what this region is known for.

5. In conclusion, I have determined that the most dramatic change that took place out of these time lapses is Fort McMurray because of the complete transformation it had from just a large green area to a massive industrial region. I believe that some places change more than others because of new found economic opportunities, dramatic increase in population density, and changing economic statuses among diverse populations. Some of the biggest impacts I can see coming out of these changes include changes in natural ecosystems, increase in a regions' gross domestic product (GDP), and political strife due to rapid expansion and land rights.

1. The latitude, or the measurement of how North or South a location is, of Draper, UT is approximately 40.5247 degrees North, whereas Tonga has a latitude of 21.1790 degrees South.

2. As Earth gets farther away from the Sun, the tilt of the Earth's axis makes it so the portion of the planet tilting away from the Sun, December 21st for the Northern portion and June 21st for the Southern portion, has more daylight hours, which means more heat, whereas the opposite happens for the wintertime. 

3. The tilt of the Earth gives places that are significantly North of the Equator, or the central latitude line of the Earth, more hours of sunlight as the Earth gets closer to the Sun.

4. Since the Earth is tilted towards the same place all throughout its revolution around the Sun, during the June Solstice, the time of year when the Northern part of Earth is tilted most toward the Sun, the Northern portion of Earth gets more energy. Vice verse with the Southern portion of Earth during the December Solstice. 

5. Since the Earth is tilted towards the same direction at all times, when Summer starts up on June 21 in the Northern half of Earth, days are much longer. However, in the Southern portion of Earth, since it is tilted away from the Sun, the days are much shorter. The complete opposite occurs on December 21.

America: Rise of the Continents:

Near the beginning of the film, one of the guests was talking about folding and how it can show the formation of various regions. The same guest used the minerals to identify when and how the rock was formed. The narrator informs the viewer that continental division made it so New York is no longer a massive mountain range as it would have been if Pangea hadn't divided. Professor David Elliott, when examining the history of the Grand Canyon, discusses a lot about the effects of weathering that shaped the rocks found in modern day Grand Canyon. He discusses wind patterns and how erosion made it possible for the footprints of ancient wildlife to be preserved.

           The film discusses how the rocks on the palisade side of the Hudson River formed by cooling and also how the joints within the rocks made it so the cooling process could be completed. They were formed by the insertion of magma and the volcanic ash made it so the global climate was altered significantly. Another concept discussed in the film is the Mid-Atlantic Region where the volcanic vents are constantly pushing out magma that then cools and forms fresh new rock.

          The dormant volcano found in Bolivia contains veins of silver that are worth a lot of money and are mined by locals. There is steam emerging near the volcano and the water is coming from the Pacific Ocean nearly 400 miles west. The film also discusses subduction when discussing the source of the silver in the mine and how the water traveled from the Pacific Ocean to the Andes.

         It was really interesting to learn about the lithium reserves in Bolivia and how lithium is used to make efficient batteries for electric vehicles. The film also discusses how subduction made it possible for the lithium deposit to be so abundant in Bolivia when the Andes started to form. The film also discusses the rich biodiversity found in the Amazon Rainforest thanks to the Andes' creation. The unique ecosystem found in the Amazon showcases how the continental divide made it possible for biodiversity to exist and for new species to exist. 

        The film also discusses hot llamas adapted to the environment of the Andes and how they were introduced to the harsh climates of Bolivia. It was also really interesting to see how the land bridge, now known as Central America, was formed and made it possible for species to mingle and create a much more diverse biosphere in both North and South America.

Overall, I really liked this film because it helped me apply my knowledge to natural geological processes and helped reinforce what I already knew before taking this course. I feel like the examples shown in the film also helped me remember that the concepts we learn in the textbook can be applied in the real world. It was really interesting to learn how both North and South America formed and what they would have formed if Pangea didn't divide. I also enjoyed how the film showed how modern day cultures were formed by the division of Pangea.

1. The Mineral Cycle is the most important biogeochemical cycle to learn when trying to understand algal blooms in Utah Lake.

2. The Mineral Cycle uses gaseous pathways to help elements, such as phosphorus, move from bedrock to soil, and along sedimentary routes. This helps the cycle of elements continue through the ocean and ground water. 

3. Humans are implicated n the algal bloom problems on Utah Lake by the fact that our waste water treatment plants discharge certain chemicals and elements that can occasionally slip out and the only way we can prevent this from happening is to either stop the chemicals before they reach the water, which is expensive, or to fight the chemical buildup with chemicals that kill the harmful elements. 

4. Utah Lake is connected with other waterways in the state through connection routes such as the Jordan River than connect Utah Lake with the Great Salt Lake.

5. Algal blooms on Utah Lake could effect other waterways in the state by a trickle down effect where the harmful chemicals or elements could go down stream or be transported by some other way and effect the water supplies of neighboring communities.

6. According to the article on ksl.com, the algal bloom has resulted in high mortality rates among fish, bat, and bird populations.

7a. According to the article on wired.com, "One solution would be for cities to upgrade their sewage treatment plants to remove nutrients before they ever hit the water." The article goes on to explain the fact that this solution is expensive and requires a lot of planning. This solution seems to be the most straight forward and would be a good investment long term. However, one concern relating to this solution is the fact that taxpayers may want to put their money towards more pressing issues that have a more substantial impact.

7b. Also on the article on wired.com, "some [cities] choose to algae-killing toxic chemicals like copper sulphate into lakes or add clay that binds up phosphorous at the bottom." This seems to be a more cost-effective approach and would also provide a more immediate solution. However, there could be side effects from using toxic chemicals, such as poisoning caused by inhalation of those chemicals by lake-goers. 

7c. One final solution could be a balance between the two previous proposed solutions. ETHICS IN ANALYTICS

 

Analytics is used in nearly every industry ranging from major retailers to professional sport franchises. Over the past several years, an investigation has been conducted into the Houston Astros, a Major League Baseball (MLB) team who has found recent success, into their use of analytics. In professional Baseball, pitch signs are used between a pitcher and catcher to communicate how the pitcher should throw the ball (e.g., fast ball, curve ball). The investigation concluded that, “the team’s staff and players developed an illegal approach to stealing pitch signs from catchers that helped hitters anticipate what pitch was coming.” (Davenport, 2020)

To put this issue into context, “MLB rules allowed a runner standing on second base to steal signs and relay them to the batter, but the MLB rules strictly forbade using electronic means to decipher signs.” (University of Texas, McCombs School of Business, n.d.). During the investigation, it was found that the organization created an algorithm to predict pitch signs, thus violating the rules.

Eventually, the MLB found the algorithm and ended up fining the Astros’ $5 million dollars and stripping them of multiple draft picks.

Cloud AutoML has the potential to disrupt the Data Science ecosystem by automating much of the Machine Learning Lifecycle. However, it also comes with the caveat of unintentional bias and bad data wrangling. As mentioned in the article, Data Engineering is arguably the most tedious part of Data Science and there have been many attempts to automate this, but to no avail. Rather, companies invest in Data Engineers to work alongside Data Scientists and ML Engineers to gain a better understanding of what data needs to be where and how it should be formatted. Cloud AutoML could help with this process by using Large Language Models to generate data models based on the business needs, identify data quality issues, and preprocess data accordingly. There will likely be issues regarding computing costs and requirements for stakeholders to disclose basic statistical measures with their shareholders, though this will be solved with time.

1. B-trees are an indexing method used by relational databases to quickly sort through vast amounts of data stored in a clustered index. Rather than storing data in heaps that force the database query engine to refer to the IAM every time it wants to locate a record, it uses a B-tree to logically identify the data attached to the index key.
    B-trees dramatically improve the performance of queries by sorting the data logically in each node as a traditional page  of data. This enables the query engine to use the B-tree to find the specific value rather than iterating through all pages for a specific item.
  1. Other database query methods are less valuable because they force the query engine to scan a heap of data, or an unordered list of pages, to find a specific piece of data matching the query being executed. This then cuts the performance in half because the query engine must reference the IAM every time it wants to locate a specific piece of data.
  2. B-trees must change over time because the underlying table data changes over time. If all customer records with a CustomerID between 100 and 200 are removed, then a node on a B-tree stating “100-150” or “150-200” will become obsolete, thus becoming a waste of space. To cope with these changes, B-trees constantly update the nodes and pages of data as new data is added and removed from the table.

Citizen of a Community: From the viewpoint of a citizen of a community, to be "Statistically literate" means that the citizen understands how to interpret quantitative reports and communicate the information with someone in the community who may not be statistically literate. The importance of being statistically literate lies in the fact that exabytes of data are being produced on a daily basis around the globe, thus allowing governmental agencies and organizations to generate thousands of reports related to crime rates, tax spend, and education expenses. In order for the average citizen to understand the information found in these reports, they must be statistically literate. These reports are also critical for political campaigns and are the baseline for making healthy societal change.

1. (b). Business Context: In a business context, being "statistically literate" means that a member of an organization understands how to interpret quantitative reports for the purpose of increasing financial earnings, improving production efficiency, and lowering organizational expenses. The importance of being statistically literate lies in the fact that with the increasing amount of data being generated by businesses, leaders and employees within a business need to understand how to interpret these data and how it impacts their respective roles and responsibilities within their organization. One of the universal requirements to be an effective senior manager in 2022 is quantitative literacy. This is another term for being statistically literate, and it holds the same importance.

Argument: On pg. 506, Doris states that, "Aristotle thinks that virtue is typified by the performance of right actions in the most difficult and demanding circumstances" However, virtue must then be perceived as also performing the right actions in the lightest and least demanding circumstances This then implies that for an individual to be virtuous, they must perform the right action at all times, which is not always possible. Textbook Chapter 3:

1. Critical Thinking Questions: On pg. 28, the text states, "Virtue ethicists tend to see ethical principles as being inherent in the world and as being discoverable by means of rational reflection and disciplined living." Does this imply that virtue ethicists believe their are a few foundational ethical rules and several others that apply to certain circumstances? If so, how does one come to discover the ethical rules that apply to certain circumstances?

2. Critical Thinking Questions: Also on pg. 28, the text states, "Aristotle believed that our purpose is to pursue our proper human end, eudaimonia, which is best understood as human flourishing or living well." What is Aristotle's definition of living well? Can a person live well without being happy?

3. Argument: On pg. 28, in the section discussing Aristotle's views on eudaimonia, it seems as if Aristotle believes that if one lives a virtuous life, they will have guaranteed happiness. If this was the case, then human suffering would not cause a person to not have happiness. Therefore, living a virtuous life does not guarantee happiness, it just improves the chances of achieving happiness.

4. Observation: On pg. 28, the text implies that Aristotle believes that living a virtuous life guarantees happiness. However, it does not mention human suffering and his views on how that can hurt the chances of achieving human happiness.

5. Basic Questions: On pg. 29, the text states, "The cultivation of virtue must be accompanied by a cultivation of rationality." What's the difference between virtue and rationality? How does a person cultivate rationality?

6. Critical Thinking Questions: On pg. 29, the text states, "The virtuous act is the one that falls between the extremes [in a decision-making situation] of what is deficient and what is excessive relative to the situation." Who or what determines the virtuous act in a given situation? Are there multiple virtuous acts that can take place in a given situation?

7. Observation: On pp. 28-30, the text implies that making virtuous decisions and participating in virtuous acts is an individual choice, rather than a societal or cultural norm. This is interesting considering there are laws in place that states what you can or can not do in a particular situation (e.g., the "Stand Your Ground" laws).

8. Observation: On pg. 31, the text implies that Aquinas's views on ethics and rationality have a lot in common, yet Aquinas focused more on the religious side of things rather than the contemporary. It seems that both of these philosophers have very good perspectives on ethical issues and rationality, yet their perspectives almost seem to contradict each other in a given real-world situation.

Nicomachean Ethics Book 1/2:

1. Basic Question: On pg. 41, Aristotle states, "Every craft and every line of inquiry, and likewise every action and decision, seems to seek some good..." How does every action or question 'seek some good' if there are some actions that are exclusively intended to harm?

2. Basic Question: On pg. 42, Aristotle states, "And [this good] appears to be characteristic of political science." What is Aristotle referring to this this context? Has the definition of political science changed since Aristotle's time?

3. Critical Thinking Question: On pg. 42, the text states, "if the good is the same for a city as for an individual, still the good of the city is apparently a greater and more complete good to acquire and preserve." How are the goals and achievements of a city or state government more important than those of an individual?

4. Observation: On pg. 42, Aristotle determines that "it is finer and more divine to acquire and preserve [the glory] for a people and for cities." From my perspective, the city-states on ancient Greece and Rome were so important that individual goals and achievements seemed to be overruled by the conquests achieved by the city-states.

5. Critical Thinking Question: On pg. 42, Aristotle states, "hence the good judge in a given area is the person educated in that area..." If this is the case, then why are modern-day judges not placed into situations in which they are educated (e.g., a judge with a background in business be involved in judging white-collar crimes)?

6. Observation: I find it very interesting that Aristotle argues on pg. 42 that a youth "is not a suitable student of political science; for he lacks experience" because in today's society, 18-year-olds have the right to vote, yet they have very little experience in life and may be voting for things that may not have any impact on them for several years.

7. Observation: Aristotle brings up a good point on pg. 42 when he compares the differing views on happiness between "the many" and "the wise". Put simply, he states that the many believe happiness to be subjective to their circumstances, whereas the wise believe there to be a general good from which all other goods, or happiness, comes from. This seems to still be the case in today's society where "the many" want short-term satisfaction, and "the wise" believe there to be a source of long-term happiness.

8. Argument: On pg. 43, Aristotle states, "things are known in two ways, for some are known to us, known without qualification." However, there are situations where we convince ourselves that we know something, yet we don't know anything about the topic or situation. Therefore, there are a three ways in which things are known.

9. Observation: Throughout this passage, it seems as if Aristotle is a very black and white thinker, meaning he views things as either a or b, rather than there being multiple other possibilities. One example of this is on pg. 43 when he states, "He who grasps everything himself is best of all; he who is noble also who listens to one who has spoken well; but he who neither grasps it himself nor takes to heart what he hears from another is a useless man."

10. Basic Question: On pg. 43, Aristotle states, "if this is the sort of life [a person] leads, no one would count him happy, except to defend a philosopher's paradox." What is a philosopher's paradox?

  1. Critical Thinking Question: On pg. 65, the text states, "Feminists, however, pointed out that this "universal" perspective was a specifically white male perspective." If this is the case, then do white women or other minorities see the world vastly different from the general population?
  2. Basic Question: Based off the information found on pg. 65, were there no female philosophers in the early Twentieth Century? It seems like either there were no women interested or they weren't given the opportunity to publish their theories or works.
  3. Observation: The text states on pp. 65-66 that men focus on the principles of justice and responsibility whereas women focus on the principles of relationships and kindness. These perspectives seem to be well-represented in ancient philosophical accounts.
  4. Argument: On pg. 66, Carol Gilligan claims that, "a woman exhibits a focus on caring for the self in order to ensure survival…" After analyzing this statement, I have determined that both males and females act in self-interest before helping others for the reason of survival. If this were not the case, females would be the only humans alive. Therefore, both males and females act according to Care Ethics.
  5. Observation: On pg. 67, the text explains the principles of natural care and ethical care as introduced by Nel Noddings. These principles seem to be very similar to those of Utilitarianism, where the individual needs to make decisions based on what will best fulfill the happiness, or care, of others.
  6. Basic Question: On pg. 67, the text states that, "In service occupations, such as a flight attendant, Bartky says the employee must force their own feelings into the background, and be nice (for example)…" Does this imply that Feminism is wrong in assuming that only women have the capacity to care for others on a deep level in this environment?
  7. Observation: Based off Bartky's argument on pp. 67-68 regarding women's role in the household, it seems like the role of women has changed dramatically as many women are now entering the workforce and allowing the fathers to take care of their children.
  8. Argument: On pg. 68, The text states, "Women and girls are taught to take pride in the production of [children, household maintenance, care of children and men, and sex], while men learn that these are women's work, and therefore not their responsibility. I personally grew up with a stay-at-home dad who was responsible for taking care of my brother and I as well as completing household maintenance. Therefore, generally speaking, not all men are taught that these categories are women's work.
  9. Critical Thinking Question: On pg. 68, the text states, "persons are understood to have varying degrees of dependence and interdependence." Do men and women have different degrees of dependence and interdependence? If so, how can this be measured?
  10. Observation: On pg. 70, the text explains the notion that modern-day feminism in philosophy encompasses the idea that autonomy doesn't mean entirely independent, it simply means independent but with the ability to ask for help when needed. Such as a plane with auto-pilot with a pilot there just in case anything goes wrong or needs attention.

Lindemann:

  1. Critical Thinking Question: On pg. 417, Lindemann states, "I argue that family members have a special responsibility to hold on to the person's identity for [them]…" If the person in question has no family around, or no family that is physically or mentally capable of taking care of them, whose responsibility is it to take care of this person?
  2. Observation: On pp. 417-41, Lindemann explains the process of how an individual forms their own identity and how their identity if formed for them. This seems to be slightly subjective as in today's world of social media and constant propaganda, an individual's identity can be forced upon them by society.
  3. Argument: On pg. 418, Lindemann states, "if families impose identities on their children that stunt their emotional, intellectual, or physical growth… unless the children later manage to contest and repair these damaged identities, their lives will go badly for them." There are many stories of individuals who were abused as kids or grew up in environments where their parents weren't great influences, yet they still were able to turn out alright or be outright successful. Therefore, if families impose negative identities on their children, there is no guarantee the children will be unsuccessful in life.
  4. Basic Question: On pg. 418, Lindemann states, "[families] are primarily responsible for holding the child in [their identity]" Does this vary between cultures? If so, how do children develop and maintain their identities without their families or social climate?
  5. Observation: On pp. 418-419, Lindemann explains that our identities are shaped and maintained by various aspects of our lives, including our homes, neighbors, and material possessions. This seems to be a very fundamental part of the human experience, to know one's self as accurately as possible. The perspective on one's identity may change, but their true identity will never change once it has been fully developed.
  6. Critical Thinking Question: On pg. 420, Lindemann explains the notion that to properly portray another person's identity, the proportions need to be set right. If this is the case, then why are politicians pictured as lizards who are trying to turn the United States into a socialist nation?
  7. Critical Thinking Question: On pg. 420, Lindemann explains the notions that if we classify an entire group of people around a single identity, we are going against the social norms of morality. If this is the case. Then why are racial stereotypes so prevalent in today's society?
  8. Critical Thinking Question: On pg. 421, Lindemann shares the example of the grandmother with Alzheimer's who is being taken care of by her granddaughter and son. However, in the case where a felon wake up from a coma with little memory, is it morally acceptable to explain what he has done?
  9. Observation: On pp. 420-421, when Lindemann is explaining the notion of good and bad holding of a person's identity, it has become clear that we hold many identities on a daily basis, when we call our parents or grandparents, when we do an act of kindness to our next-door neighbor.
  10. Basic Question: On pg. 423, Lindemann explains society's role in holding identities. Are there specific laws in place the prohibit society from altering people's identities whether in a good or bad connotation?
